{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":3,"markdown":"At the national level, the mean DQA score improved from 94% in 2019 to 96% in 2025. National mean scores are high, showing that on average, Sierra Leone's HMIS data is close to the desired quality standard.

Across districts, all scores remained above 90% in 2025.

Although many facility-months don’t meet all criteria, they are close on average — suggesting that small improvements in reporting practices could bring most facilities above the threshold."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"4dc02c21-29da-4a01-9812-469deedaaac8","moduleId":"m001","selectedReplicantValue":""}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in data quality"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Institutional deliveries rose gradually through 2024 before climbing more sharply in 2025, reaching nearly 24,000 by mid-2025, reflecting stronger uptake of facility births.

Postnatal care for newborns increased steadily, reaching about 21,000 by mid-2025, indicating improvements in early follow-up after delivery.

Postnatal care for mothers followed a similar upward trend, with notable gains in 2025 to nearly 24,000 visits, pointing to stronger continuity of care across the maternal–newborn period.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"a6d02d7b-628f-40b2-b0de-6550154525a0","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in deliveries and postnatal care services","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 visits were consistently above expectations in 2025, averaging ~26,900 per month vs. ~24,200 expected (~11% higher), with June 2025 ~26,200 visits (~9% above expected).

ANC4 visits stayed close to expected levels, averaging ~19,300 per month vs. ~18,800 expected (~3% higher), with June 2025 ~18,900 visits (~5% above expected).

Both indicators align with expected trends, though ANC1 shows clearer gains. Continuity remains a concern, as fewer women complete ANC4 compared to ANC1."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"f13bc674-ef5d-4619-9723-9bf804e56ee5","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC1 shows slight surpluses in 2025, while ANC4 stays near trend, but continuity gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"In 2025, deliveries rose steadily above expected levels, reaching ~14% higher than trend by June. This shows stronger uptake of facility-based births — a key entry point for maternal–newborn care.

Newborn PNC visits rose to ~8% above expected by June 2025, but gains are smaller than for deliveries. While gains are smaller than for deliveries, volumes still reached about 90% of delivery levels, suggesting some newborns are not receiving timely follow-up after birth.

Maternal PNC visits climbed to ~9% above expected by June 2025. PNC for mothers reached about 93% of delivery levels, pointing to modest but persistent gaps in linking facility births with postpartum care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"49a16d71-3f95-4004-84d5-e0a101575c2b","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Institutional deliveries and PNC visits rise above expected levels in 2025, but continuity of care gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1: Consistently below expectations in 2025, averaging ~64,200 vs. ~71,100 expected (~10% lower). July 2025 was ~66,300 (~10% lower).

ANC4: Stayed close to expected, averaging ~21,700 vs. ~22,400 expected (~3% lower). July 2025 was ~22,100 (~5% lower).

 ANC1 shows persistent shortfalls, and fewer women continue to ANC4, underscoring a continuity gap in antenatal care. Overall, both indicators align closely with expectations, but ANC1 shows a higher persistent shortfall compared to expected service use."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"f13bc674-ef5d-4619-9723-9bf804e56ee5","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Antenatal Care Service Use Similar to Expected Trends"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"Institutional deliveries rose gradually through 2024 before climbing more sharply in 2025, reaching nearly 24,000 by mid-2025, reflecting stronger uptake of facility births.

